CRITICAL: prioritize factual, source-backed findings and avoid false positives.
Treat the correlated context as a ranking aid, not proof by itself.
Only call something CONFIRMED when the raw tool evidence supports it.
Focus on sensitive data exposure in SAFE evidence format only:
- Exposure type and affected scope (counts, endpoint/table names)
- Sanitized examples only (mask identifiers/secrets)
- Source tool tags (e.g. [run_web_vulns], [run_api_test], [company_exposure:operational]) for each claim
- Confidence labels: CONFIRMED vs POSSIBLE
- Explicitly state scan gaps/timeouts to avoid overclaiming

Prioritize the assess surface that matters most to a company first: admin exposure, identity/auth weaknesses, debug or operational endpoints, backup/config/storage leaks, public data-bearing APIs, and business-data routes. Explicitly prioritize payment and financial impact: zero or manipulated payment acceptance, payment/order/wallet IDOR, refund abuse (run_payment_financial). Then IDOR, leaked secrets, business-logic flaws, race conditions. These are how users lose money and differentiate Diverg. For crypto or trading platforms (e.g. axiom.trade, Solana terminals): also prioritize user leakage (other users' wallet/position/trade data), wallet/position IDOR, and client-side exposure of keys or balances. Do not let commodity SQLi/XSS dominate the report unless the evidence shows they are the highest-risk issue.

In WHAT WE TESTED and TOP FINDINGS, reflect these finding buckets if present: Misconfiguration, Reconnaissance Value, Transport and Browser Security, Access Control, Data Exposure, Exploitation Path, Operational Exposure.
Use target profiles and assess-surface highlights from the correlated context to explain why some issues deserve priority.
In LIKELY assess PATHS, prefer the ranked path hypotheses from the correlated context and explain why they are likely.
In DETECTION AND READINESS, use the correlated readiness score as a starting point, then adjust only if raw evidence clearly supports it.
If recommended_next_tests is present in the context, mention it in the report (e.g. RECOMMENDED NEXT TESTS or FOLLOW-UP) so the operator can run those checks.
If breach_exposure is present (domain in HIBP/IntelX etc.), include a assess for data exposure in / DATA EXPOSURE note and state clearly: We cannot determine whether data was sold on the dark web; consider threat intel or assess for data exposure in monitoring for your domain/emails.

THREAT READINESS MODE IS ENABLED. Include additional defensive sections:
- MITRE ATT&CK style tactic/technique tags for major findings where applicable
- EARLY WARNING SIGNALS (specific telemetry/log indicators)
- SOC USE CASES (3-8 concrete detection ideas for SIEM/EDR/identity/network)
- CONTROL GAPS and readiness score (0-100)

Now write your report using the REPORTING FORMAT. Put SENSITIVE DATA EXPOSURE section FIRST with anything you found. If no sensitive data was accessible, state that clearly.
